The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Two Tata firms post dismal numbers
                                                                                                               Two Tata firms post dismal numbers
          OUR BUREAU                                          TROUBLED TIMES    
	Jan. 30: Tata Motors has reported its first quarterly loss in seven years as poor demand hobbled sales.        
	The automotive giant suffered a net loss of Rs 263.26 crore for the quarter ended December 31, 2008 compared with a net profit of Rs 499 crore in the corresponding previous period. Revenues fell 34.4 per cent to Rs 4,758.62 crore in the third quarter of 2008 compared with Rs 7,251.83 crore in the corresponding period last year.         
	Foreign exchange losses worsened the profitability of the company.         
	According to a Tata Motors statement, The loss after tax includes a notional exchange loss on revaluation of forex borrowings, deposits and loans given of Rs 226.52 crore.        
	Poor liquidity conditions, non-availability of consumer finance and a contraction in freight movement in many segments of the industry sparked a 61 per cent fall in the demand for medium and heavy commercial vehicles.         
	As a result, the companys sales volumes fell 31.7 per cent to 98,760 vehicles. Revenues for the first nine months of 2008-09 stood at Rs 18,765 crore, a fall of 6.1 per cent compared with Rs 19,981.30 crore in the corresponding period last year.        
	Tea performance        
	Tata Tea today reported a big decline in consolidated net profit at Rs 396.12 crore for the December quarter against a net profit of Rs 1,292.22 crore for the same quarter in the last financial year.        
	According to a Tata Tea statement, the profit after tax dropped mainly due to the one-time profit on sale of investments in Energy Brands Inc during the corresponding quarter of the previous year.        
	The managing director of the company, Percy T. Siganporia, will move to London.         
	The company release said Siganporia would continue to be the managing director and also be responsible for global manufacturing operations as well as buying and blending, supply chain and related activities for some regions.                                                                                                                                        
